Items.Title: Jimmy Carter, Peacemaking President Amid Crises, Is Dead at 100
Items.Summary: Rising from Georgia farmland to the White House, he oversaw the historic Camp David peace accords, but his one-term presidency was waylaid by troubles at home and abroad.

Items.Title: Among Presidents, Jimmy Carter Was the Odd Man Out
Items.Summary: Jimmy Carter’s relationship with his successors in the Oval Office, both Republicans and fellow Democrats, was generally tense because of his outspokenness. That never mattered to him.

Items.Title: Jimmy Carter’s Quiet but Monumental Work in Global Health
Items.Summary: In his decades as a former president, he and his wife, Rosalynn Carter, helped bring lifesaving treatments and sanitation to poor people around the world.

Items.Title: Jimmy Carter Dies at 100, and Questions Surround South Korean Plane Crash
Items.Summary: Plus, why coffee prices are soaring.

Items.Title: Video of South Korea Plane Crash Offers Clues to Cause, but No Immediate Answers
Items.Summary: The cause of the crash probably won’t be determined for months, with investigators expected to focus on a wide range of issues.

Items.Title: Boeing Shares Drop After South Korea Plane Crash
Items.Summary: A widely used Boeing aircraft, the 737-800, was involved in Sunday’s crash-landing of a Jeju Air flight that killed 179 people.

Items.Title: The Men Who Use Instagram to Groom Child Influencers
Items.Summary: Photographers and other men offer to build online followings for young girls, but some are pedophiles who work with parents to sexualize them.

Items.Title: Social Media Companies Face Global Tug-of-War Over Free Speech
Items.Summary: President-elect Donald J. Trump’s picks for the F.C.C. and F.T.C. have vowed to remove censorship online. That conflicts with European regulators who are pushing for stricter moderation.

Items.Title: How Top Pollsters Grade 2024’s Polls
Items.Summary: Despite a pretty accurate year, the pre-election polls once again underestimated support for Donald Trump. Does that make it a successful polling cycle, or not?

Items.Title: D&D Rule Changes Involving Race and Identity Divide Players
Items.Summary: The role-playing game replaced “race” with “species” and divorced several character traits from biological identity. Some longtime players are upset (as is Elon Musk).

Items.Title: The Number of Murders Kept Falling This Year, But Fear of Crime Persists
Items.Summary: Crime was a talking point on the presidential campaign trail. But after a spike during the pandemic, murders have been dropping steadily, including in big cities like Chicago and San Francisco.

Items.Title: Lebanon’s Economy Reels From Israel-Hezbollah War
Items.Summary: The conflict between Israel and Hezbollah may be suspended, but the damage is immense. “We came out of this war with nothing,” one man said.

Items.Title: Cold Takes More Infant Lives in Gaza, Adding to the War’s Civilian Toll
Items.Summary: The Gazan health ministry says at least five babies have died from the cold in the last week. Displaced families have little more than tents and tarps to protect them from the weather.

Items.Title: Shen Yun Needed Publicity. The Epoch Times Wrote 17,000 Articles.
Items.Summary: A publisher that rose to prominence promoting right-wing conspiracy theories has also served as sword and shield for the dance group and the religious movement behind it.

Items.Title: Where Is Russia Finding New Soldiers? Wherever It Can.
Items.Summary: From murder suspects to immigrants to a former Olympic gold medalist, Russia pressures those it thinks should fight in Ukraine.

Items.Title: Five Laws Going Into Effect for New York in 2025
Items.Summary: Changes are coming to paid family leave, insulin costs, restaurant reservations, gym membership cancellations and protections for fashion industry workers.

Items.Title: Democratic N.Y. Lawmakers Brace for Risks of a Trump Administration
Items.Summary: After President-elect Donald J. Trump’s gains in New York, lawmakers plan to focus on high costs and crime while safeguarding policies about immigration and abortion.

Items.Title: Samantha Power: The Humanitarian Legacy of Jimmy Carter
Items.Summary: Jimmy Carter viewed his embrace of human rights as a means of restoring faith in America.

Items.Title: Jimmy Carter’s Life Was One Big Trust Exercise
Items.Summary: What the 39th president did before he got to the White House is as interesting as what came after.

Items.Title: Breaking Was Supposed to Break Out in 2024. It Didn’t.
Items.Summary: It was a 50-year journey from the streets of New York to the Paris Olympic Games. But a would-be celebration turned into something of a debacle.

Items.Title: Hydropower Was Ecuador’s Answer to Climate Change. Until the Drought Hit.
Items.Summary: An extraordinary drought has drained Ecuador’s rivers and reservoirs, leading to power outages of up to 14 hours. Some fear this is the beginning of a larger global crisis.

Items.Title: How TSMC’s Arizona Chip Plant Seeded a Tiny Taipei in the Desert
Items.Summary: Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, a global tech giant, brought thousands of workers from Asia to the Phoenix suburbs for jobs at a plant that the Biden administration helped fund.

Items.Title: Olivia Hussey, Star of a Renowned ‘Romeo and Juliet,’ Dies at 73
Items.Summary: Her passionate portrayal of Juliet in Franco Zeffirelli’s 1968 film adaptation won enduring acclaim. In 2023, she sued over the circumstances of a nude scene.

Items.Title: ‘Wicked’ Green, ‘Room Next Door’ Red and ‘Substance’ Yellow: It’s a Bold Season
Items.Summary: Some potential contenders were especially vivid. Production and costume designers explain the conundrums they faced and their surprising solutions.

Title: National
Description: The Washington Post's national news coverage. Get the latest national news, featuring national security, science and the courts. Read breaking national news headlines from across the U.S.

Items.Title: What we know about Jimmy Carter’s funeral plans
Items.Summary: President Joe Biden said he has been in touch with Carter’s family and started the process to hold a state funeral.

Items.Title: How Jimmy Carter helped build 4,390 homes with Habitat for Humanity
Items.Summary: Carter, who died Sunday at age 100, made his volunteer work building affordable and decent housing for Habitat for Humanity a significant part of his legacy.

Items.Title: 11 facts about Jimmy Carter that may surprise you
Items.Summary: The peanut farmer-turned-president, who died Sunday at 100, put solar panels on the White House and once spent 89 seconds inside a melting nuclear reactor.

Items.Title: His work after the White House made Jimmy Carter a standout
Items.Summary: The former president traveled the globe for more than four decades to raise houses, health, peace and democracy.

Items.Title: Video shows New York corrections staff beat inmate hours before he died
Items.Summary: The New York attorney general released body camera video of corrections officers beating a handcuffed inmate hours before he died.

Items.Title: Oklahoma AG drops charge against officer who threw 71-year-old to ground
Items.Summary: The prosecutor who charged the police officer with assault said she was “surprised and disappointed” by the Oklahoma attorney general’s decision.
